 Blush\n|[[Barbara Carrera]]\n|-\n|Patricia Fearing\n|[[Prunella Gee]]\n|-\n|Lady in Bahamas\n|[[Valerie Leon]]\n|-\n|Nicole\n|Saskia Cohen Tanugi\n|}\n<!-- Do not add the Queen and Happy and Glorious: she is not a Bond Girl. If you wonder why not, please read the first line of this article -->\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Game || ! scope=\"col\"|Bond girl || ! scope=\"col\"|Actress\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | ''[[007: Agent Under Fire|Agent Under Fire]]'' || Zoe Nightshade || [[Caron Pascoe]] (voice)\n|-\n|Adrian Malprave\n|Eve Karpf (voice)\n|-\n|Dr. Natalya Damescu\n|Beatie Edney (voice)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | ''[[James Bond 007: Nightfire|Nightfire]]'' || Dominique Paradis || [[Lena Reno]] (voice)\n|-\n|Zoe Nightshade\n|[[Jeanne Mori]] (voice)\n|-\n|Alura McCall\n|[[Kimberley Davies]] (voice)\n|-\n|Makiko Hayashi\n|[[Tamlyn Tomita]] (voice)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | ''[[James Bond 007: Everything or Nothing|Everything or Nothing]]'' || Serena St. Germaine || [[Shannon Elizabeth]]\n|-\n|Dr. Katya Nadanova\n|[[Heidi Klum]]\n|-\n|Miss Nagai \n|[[Misaki Ito]]\n|-\n|Mya Starling\n|[[M\u00fda]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[GoldenEye: Rogue Agent]]'' || Pussy Galore || [[Jeannie Elias]] (voice)\n|-\n|Xenia Onatopp\n|[[Jenya Lano]] (voice)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | ''[[007: From Russia with Love|From Russia with Love]]'' || Tatiana Romanova || [[Daniela Bianchi]] (likeness), [[Kari Wahlgren]] (voice)\n|-\n|Eva Adara\n|[[Maria Menounos]]\n|-\n|Elizabeth Stark\n|[[Natasha Bedingfield]]\n|-\n| ''[[James Bond 007: Blood Stone|Blood Stone]]'' || Nicole Hunter || [[Joss Stone]] (likeness and voice)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[GoldenEye 007 (2010 video game)|GoldenEye 007]]'' || Xenia Onatopp  || [[Kate Magowan]] (likeness and voice)\n|-\n|Natalya Simonova\n|[[Kirsty Mitchell]] (likeness and voice)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | ''[[007 Legends]]'' ||Holly Goodhead || [[Jane Perry (actress)|Jane Perry]]\n|-\n|Tracy Draco \n|[[Diana Rigg]] (likeness), [[Nicola Walker]] (voice)\n|-\n|Pam Bouvier\n|[[Carey Lowell]]\n|-\n|Jinx \n|[[Gabriela Montaraz]] (likeness), [[Madalena Alberto]] (voice)\n|-\n|Pussy Galore\n|[[Honor Blackman]] (likeness), [[Natasha Little]] (voice)\n|}\n\n==Documentary==\nIn 2002 former Bond girl [[Maryam d'Abo]] co-wrote the book ''[[Bond Girls Are Forever]]: The Women of James Bond''. This book later became a DVD exclusive documentary featuring d'Abo and other Bond girls, including Ursula Andress. In some locations, the documentary was released as a gift with the purchase of ''[[Die Another Day]]'' on DVD. The featurette was included on the DVD release of ''Casino Royale'' (2006).\n\n==Critical studies==\nIn 2003, scholarly critiques of Pussy Galore and Miss Moneypenny, authored by Professors Elizabeth Ladenson and Tara Brabazon, respectively, were published in ''The James Bond Phenomenon: A Critical Reader''.<ref>Lindner, Christoph, ed., ''The James Bond Phenomenon: A Critical Reader'' (Manchester University, 2003), chs. 11\u201312.</ref> In 2009, researchers at [[Cleveland State University]] and [[Kent State University]] published an article, ''Shaken and Stirred: A Content Analysis of Women's Portrayals in James Bond Films'', which provided a quantitative content analysis of 195 female characters appearing in twenty James Bond films.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Shaken and Stirred: A Content Analysis of Women's Portrayals in James Bond Films|doi=10.1007/s11199-009-9644-2 |date= |accessdate=29 March 2012 |volume=62 |issue= 11\u201312|journal=Sex Roles |pages=747\u2013761|year= 2009|last1= Neuendorf|first1= Kimberly A.|last2= Gore|first2= Thomas D.|last3= Dalessandro|first3= Amy|last4= Janstova|first4= Patricie|last5= Snyder-Suhy|first5= Sharon}}</ref>\n\nThe term ''Bond girl'' may also be considered as an anachronism, particularly in the post [[Me Too movement |#MeToo]] era, with regard to the objectification of women in film.<ref>{{cite news |title=Are Bond girls sexist? |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/culture/story/20151014-bond-women-sexy-or-just-sexist |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Child |first1=Ben |title=Time's up for James Bond: is 007 too toxic for the #MeToo era? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/30/times-up-for-james-bond-is-007-too-brutish-for-the-me-too-era |work=The Guardian |date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Film|Biography}}\n* [[Outline of James Bond]]\n* [[:Category:Bond girls]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book |last1= Comentale |first1= Edward P| last2=Watt |first2=Stephen | last3=Willman |first3=Skip | year=2005 |title= Ian Fleming & James Bond: the cultural politics of 007|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|isbn= 978-0-253-21743-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last= J\u00fctting |first= Kerstin |title=\"Grow Up, 007!\": James Bond Over the Decades: Formula Vs. Innovation|publisher= GRIN Verlag|year=2007|isbn= 978-3-638-85372-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Lipp |first= Deborah |title= The Ultimate James Bond Fan Book |year=2006 |publisher=Sterling & Ross Publishers|location=New York |isbn= 978-0-9766372-8-8 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{JamesBond}}\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{James Bond characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bond Girl}}\n[[Category:Lists of actors by role]]\n[[Category:Lists of fictional females]]\n[[Category:Lists of fictional sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Lists of James Bond characters|Girl]]\n[[Category:Bond girls| ]]\n\n[[de:Figuren aus James-Bond-Filmen#Die Bond-Girls]]\n", "name_user": "Mdaniels5757", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reference edited withProveIt)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_girl"}
{"title_page": "John A. Willox", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:The Pall Mall Gazette (London, England), Wednesday, July 6, 1892; Issue 8515.jpg|thumb|John Archibald Willox pictured in the ''[[Pall Mall Gazette]]'' following his [[1892 Liverpool Everton by-election|election]] to Parliament]]\n'''Sir John Archibald Willox''' (9 June 1842 \u2013 9 June 1905) was a British journalist, newspaper owner and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician from [[Liverpool]]. He rose through the ranks to become the owner of the ''[[Liverpool Courier]]'' newspaper and sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1892 to 1905.<ref name=\"popular\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nWillox was born in [[Edinburgh]], the son of the journalist John Willox who also wrote several books related to shipping. His family moved to Liverpool, where he was educated at [[Liverpool College]].<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n== Career ==\nLeaving school in his mid-teens, Willox was [[apprentice]]d to the journalists Lee and Nightingale. They seconded him to the ''Liverpool Courier'', which was then published twice each week. He became a [[sub-editor]], then a partner in Tinling & Co which owned the paper. By 1863, aged only 21, he was the editor.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nUnder Willox's editorship, the paper promptly became a [[daily newspaper|daily]], with a Saturday '' Weekly Courier''. The ''Evening Courier'' was established in 1870 and became the ''Evening Express''.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nHe was a member of the [[Institute of Journalists]] and chairman of the [[Press Association]] in 1875 and 1900.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n=== Tobacco and marriage ===\nIn 1884, he was an [[executor]] of the will of [[Thomas Cope (manufacturer)|Thomas Cope]], the founder of [[Cope Bros & Co|Cope Brothers]] tobacco merchants. He became a director of the company in 1885. When Thomas's brother George died in 1888 he became [[managing director]], and married Thomas's widow,<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" /> Sara (died 1904).<ref name=\"times-sara-death\">{{cite news\n |title = Deaths \n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/694/692/161194013w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS17231759&dyn=4\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 15 December 1904\n |page = 1, column A\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\nwho had ten children from her first marriage.<ref name=\"times-sara-obit\" />\nShe was a [[philanthropist]], and 1897 she donated the \u00a315,000 cost of constructing the [[Crossley Hospital West|Sanitorium for Consumptives]] at [[Delamere Forest]] in [[Cheshire]].<ref name=\"times-sara-obit\" />\n\n=== Electricity ===\nWillox took an interest in the commercial development of [[electricity]], and became a director of several companies in that field. He became chairman of the [[Blackheath and Greenwich District Electric Light Company]], and also of the [[New St Helens and District Tramway Company]] and the [[South Lancashire Electric Traction and Power Company]].<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n=== Politics ===\n[[File:Abercromby Square 3.jpg|thumb|right|[[Abercromby Square]] in Liverpool, where Willox died]]\nAfter his marriage, Willox had become more involved in public affairs. When [[Edward Whitley (politician)|Edward Whitley]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Liverpool Everton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Everton]] died in January 1892,<ref name=\"times-1892-02-15\" />\nWillox was selected as the Conservative candidate for the [[1892 Liverpool Everton by-election|resulting by-election]].<ref name=\"times-1892-02-03\" />\n\nEverton was a Conservative [[safe seat]], which the party had held since its creation in [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]], and Willox was regarded as a strong candidate. The local [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] therefore decided not to contest the election, and Willox was returned unopposed.<ref name=\"times-1892-02-15\" /><ref name=\"gazette-by-election\" /> In honour of his election, over 100 journalists from Liverpool presented him with an [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] address.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nWillox was re-elected with a large majority at the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|general election in July 1892]],<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\" />\nand was returned unopposed in [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] and [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\" /> He was [[knight bachelor|knighted]] in Queen Victoria's [[1897 Diamond Jubilee Honours|Diamond Jubilee Honours]] in 1897.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n== Death ==\nSir John became seriously ill in late 1904.<ref name=\"times-1905-01-14\" /> When his wife Sara died, he attended her funeral at [[Anfield Cemetery]] on 17 December, but was really too ill to go out, and had to be supported by two stepsons.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nHe [[resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned from Parliament]] in February 1905 by taking the [[Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds|Chiltern Hundreds]],<ref name=\"gazette-resignation\" /> triggering [[1905 Liverpool Everton by-election|another by-election]].\nHe died on his 63rd birthday, 16 June 1905, at his home on [[Abercromby Square]], Liverpool.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|colwidth=35em\n|refs=\n<ref name=\"times-sara-obit\">{{cite news\n |title = Obituary: Lady Willox\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/694/692/161194013w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS85782415&dyn=6\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 15 December 1904\n |page = 5, col F\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"popular\">{{cite book |title=The Popular guide to the House of Commons  |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1902 |publisher=|location= |isbn= |page=92 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oIIMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA92 |accessdate=2011-01-23}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times-1892-02-03\">{{cite news\n |title = Election Intelligence: Liverpool (Everton Division)\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/823/974/161190749w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS100980291&dyn=8\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 3 February 1892\n |page = 6, column E\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times-1892-02-15\">{{cite news\n |title = Obituaries\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/823/974/161190749w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS86169135&dyn=4\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 15 January 1892\n |page = 5\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"gazette-by-election\">{{London Gazette\n |issue= 26259\n |date=19 February 1892\n |page=923\n |city=London\n }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"gazette-resignation\">{{London Gazette\n |issue= 27765\n |date=17 February 1905\n |page=1199\n |city=London\n }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times-1905-01-14\">{{cite news\n |title = Court Circular\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/857/871/161192371w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS151711790&dyn=31\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 14 January 1905\n |page = 9, column E\n |accessdate = 9 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\">{{cite news\n |title = Obituary: Sir John Willox\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/857/871/161192371w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS134672593&dyn=46\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 17 June 1905\n |page = 8, col C\n |accessdate = 9 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n |origyear=1989\n |edition=2nd\n |year=1983\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-27-2\n |pages= 139 \n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-willox| John Willox }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Liverpool Everton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Everton]]\n | years  = [[1892 Liverpool Everton by-election|1892]]\u2013[[1905 Liverpool Everton by-election|1905]]\n | before = [[Edward Whitley (politician)|Edward Whitley]]\n | after  = [[Sir John Harmood-Banner]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Willox, John Archibald}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:People educated at Liverpool College]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:The Pall Mall Gazette (London, England), Wednesday, July 6, 1892; Issue 8515.jpg|thumb|John Archibald Willox pictured in the ''[[Pall Mall Gazette]]'' following his [[1892 Liverpool Everton by-election|election]] to Parliament]]\n'''Sir John Archibald Willox''' (9 June 1842 \u2013 9 June 1905) was a British journalist, newspaper owner and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician from [[Liverpool]]. He rose through the ranks to become the owner of the ''[[Liverpool Courier]]'' newspaper and sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1892 to 1905.<ref name=\"popular\" />\n\n== Early life ==\nWillox was born in [[Edinburgh]], the son of the journalist John Willox who also wrote several books related to shipping. His family moved to Liverpool, where he was educated at [[Liverpool College]].<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n== Career ==\nLeaving school in his mid-teens, Willox was [[apprentice]]d to the journalists Lee and Nightingale. They seconded him to the ''Liverpool Courier'', which was then published twice each week. He became a [[sub-editor]], then a partner in Tinling & Co which owned the paper. By 1863, aged only 21, he was the editor.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nUnder Willox's editorship, the paper promptly became a [[daily newspaper|daily]], with a Saturday '' Weekly Courier''. The ''Evening Courier'' was established in 1870 and became the ''Evening Express''.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nHe was a member of the [[Institute of Journalists]] and chairman of the [[Press Association]] in 1875 and 1900.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n=== Tobacco and marriage ===\nIn 1884, he was an [[executor]] of the will of [[Thomas Cope (manufacturer)|Thomas Cope]], the founder of [[Cope Bros & Co|Cope Brothers]] tobacco merchants. He became a director of the company in 1885. When Thomas's brother George died in 1888 he became [[managing director]], and married Thomas's widow,<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" /> Sara (died 1904).<ref name=\"times-sara-death\">{{cite news\n |title = Deaths \n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/694/692/161194013w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS17231759&dyn=4\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 15 December 1904\n |page = 1, column A\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\nwho had ten children from her first marriage.<ref name=\"times-sara-obit\" />\nShe was a [[philanthropist]], and 1897 she donated the \u00a315,000 cost of constructing the [[Crossley Hospital West|Sanitorium for Consumptives]] at [[Delamere Forest]] in [[Cheshire]].<ref name=\"times-sara-obit\" />\n\n=== Electricity ===\nWillox took an interest in the commercial development of [[electricity]], and became a director of several companies in that field. He became chairman of the [[Blackheath and Greenwich District Electric Light Company]], and also of the [[New St Helens and District Tramway Company]] and the [[South Lancashire Electric Traction and Power Company]].<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n=== Politics ===\n[[File:Abercromby Square 3.jpg|thumb|right|[[Abercromby Square]] in Liverpool, where Willox died]]\nAfter his marriage, Willox had become more involved in public affairs. When [[Edward Whitley (politician)|Edward Whitley]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Liverpool Everton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Everton]] died in January 1892,<ref name=\"times-1892-02-15\" />\nWillox was selected as the Conservative candidate for the [[1892 Liverpool Everton by-election|resulting by-election]].<ref name=\"times-1892-02-03\" />\n\nEverton was a Conservative [[safe seat]], which the party had held since its creation in [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]], and Willox was regarded as a strong candidate. The local [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] therefore decided not to contest the election, and Willox was returned unopposed.<ref name=\"times-1892-02-15\" /><ref name=\"gazette-by-election\" /> In honour of his election, over 100 journalists from Liverpool presented him with an [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] address.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nWillox was re-elected with a large majority at the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|general election in July 1892]],<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\" />\nand was returned unopposed in [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] and [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\" /> He was [[knight bachelor|knighted]] in Queen Victoria's [[1897 Diamond Jubilee Honours|Diamond Jubilee Honours]] in 1897.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n== Death ==\nSir John became seriously ill in late 1904.<ref name=\"times-1905-01-14\" /> When his wife Sara died, he attended her funeral at [[Anfield Cemetery]] on 17 December, but was really too ill to go out, and had to be supported by two stepsons.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\nHe [[resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned from Parliament]] in February 1905 by taking the [[Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds|Chiltern Hundreds]],<ref name=\"gazette-resignation\" /> triggering [[1905 Liverpool Everton by-election|another by-election]].\nHe died on his 63rd birthday, 16 June 1905, at his home on [[Abercromby Square]], Liverpool.<ref name=\"times-willox-obit\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|colwidth=35em\n|refs=\n<ref name=\"times-sara-obit\">{{cite news\n |title = Obituary: Lady Willox\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/694/692/161194013w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS85782415&dyn=6\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 15 December 1904\n |page = 5, col F\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"popular\">{{cite book |title=The Popular guide to the House of Commons  |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1902 |publisher=|location= |isbn= |page=92 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oIIMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA92 |accessdate=2011-01-23}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times-1892-02-03\">{{cite news\n |title = Election Intelligence: Liverpool (Everton Division)\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/823/974/161190749w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS100980291&dyn=8\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 3 February 1892\n |page = 6, column E\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times-1892-02-15\">{{cite news\n |title = Obituaries\n |url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/823/974/161190749w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS86169135&dyn=4\n |newspaper = The Times\n |date = 15 January 1892\n |page = 5\n |accessdate = 8 September 2012\n}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"gazette-by-election\">{{London Gazette\n |issue= 26259\n |date=19 F